T1  - Informing the Public About a Pandemic
AU  - de Véricourt, Francis
AU  - Gurkan, Huseyin
AU  - Wang, Shouqiang
Y1  - 2021/08/12
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4016
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4016
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 6350
EP  - 6357
VL  - 67
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper explores how governments may efficiently inform the public about an epidemic to induce compliance with their confinement measures. Using an information design framework, we find the government has an incentive to either downplay or exaggerate the severity of the epidemic if it heavily prioritizes the economy over population health or vice versa. Importantly, we find that the level of economic inequality in the population has an effect on these distortions. The more unequal the disease?s economic impact on the population, the less the government exaggerates and the more it downplays the severity of the epidemic. When the government weighs the economy and population health sufficiently equally, however, the government should always be fully transparent about the severity of the epidemic. This paper was accepted by Stefan Scholtes, healthcare management.
AB  - This paper explores how governments may efficiently inform the public about an epidemic to induce compliance with their confinement measures. Using an information design framework, we find the government has an incentive to either downplay or exaggerate the severity of the epidemic if it heavily prioritizes the economy over population health or vice versa. Importantly, we find that the level of economic inequality in the population has an effect on these distortions. The more unequal the disease?s economic impact on the population, the less the government exaggerates and the more it downplays the severity of the epidemic. When the government weighs the economy and population health sufficiently equally, however, the government should always be fully transparent about the severity of the epidemic. This paper was accepted by Stefan Scholtes, healthcare management.
