T1  - The Optimality of Call Provision Terms
AU  - Powers, Eric
Y1  - 2020/12/17
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3774
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2020.3774
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 6581
EP  - 6601
VL  - 67
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - There is substantial variation in fixed-price call provision terms?call price premium and call protection. I investigate determinants of call price, call protection, and estimated call option value. Consistent with agency theory and asymmetric information models, I find that lower credit quality and opaque issuers choose higher call premiums, longer call protection, and overall less valuable call options. Higher-quality issuers, particularly financial institutions that struggle when interest rates are low, do the opposite. This paper was accepted by David Simchi-Levi, finance.
AB  - There is substantial variation in fixed-price call provision terms?call price premium and call protection. I investigate determinants of call price, call protection, and estimated call option value. Consistent with agency theory and asymmetric information models, I find that lower credit quality and opaque issuers choose higher call premiums, longer call protection, and overall less valuable call options. Higher-quality issuers, particularly financial institutions that struggle when interest rates are low, do the opposite. This paper was accepted by David Simchi-Levi, finance.
